John Edward: Language skills are essential for the citizens of the world
Scotland’s independent schools maintain a record of school excellence. This trend continued in 2018 with new excellent exam results reinforced by collective and individual success in sports, art, music and other community activities.
With more than 30,000 students across Scotland, these schools represented by the Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS) strive to offer the best level of service to students and their parents.
Independent schools work to prepare their students for higher education, the career they have chosen, and their place as citizens of the world.
As an education sector able to design and implement a tailor-made school curriculum, we find that contemporary languages remain popular and desirable subjects in schools.
Nelson Mandela said, “If you speak to a man in a language he understands, you speak to his head.
If you speak to him in his language, you speak to his heart.”
This reminds us that we cannot rely on English to build relationships and build trust with people from other countries.
If we look at the excellent results in the exams this year, we can see that languages are at the top of the ranking, with the highest success rates in independent schools.
In total, 68% of students who studied foreign languages achieved the highest grade, A.
Data collected from the 74 member schools of the SCIS show that 72% of pupils obtained the highest grade, A, in Mandarin, as well as the 72% of pupils who studied German, the 69% of pupils who studied French and the 63% of pupils who studied Spanish.
This shows that Scotland’s independent schools support foreign languages as absolutely essential skills for children and young people in the future.
Now, languages as subjects are organized just like science, technology, engineering and mathematics in the programs of independent schools and other schools.
A 2014 UK Commission on Employment and Skills survey found that 17% of employers’ difficulties in recruiting candidates are related to insufficient language skills.
Language skills are therefore increasingly vital in preparing young people for their future careers.
With more job offers requiring languages, these skills are essential in our globalized world.
No matter your career choice, a person who speaks a second language will benefit from a real benefit in the future thanks to this sustainable skill.
Being able to communicate directly with strangers will automatically put the multilingual person in front of his competitors.
According to a 2013 YouGov survey of 4,000 adults living in the UK, 75% of them did not speak a foreign language enough to hold a conversation. French was the only language spoken by a double-digit percentage (15%).
This is why investing in language learning is important for children today.
By speaking several languages, especially those of emerging economies, children will have a better chance of finding a rewarding job.
In Scotland, each school will teach different languages.
Many of them will focus on classical contemporary languages, while others will teach languages considered important for the UK in the 2020 perspective, including Mandarin or Japanese.
Whatever your child’s preferences, several languages will be available in independent schools, with specialist staff in the field.
Scottish independent schools want to offer a learning environment that will prepare children and give them the skills they need to succeed, no matter what the future holds for them.
It is clear that, in today's global business environment, languages remain of paramount importance for the future of the country, and this must be reflected in education.
Modern languages should be considered as “international communication skills”.
Independent schools will continue to offer this choice, diversity and excellence to Scottish youth.
You have to do it right.
John Edward is the Director of the Scottish Council of Independent Schools
