North Korea says disarmament can’t be done unilaterally without confidence.
On Saturday, the North Korean foreign minister told the United Nations that maintaining sanctions reinforced his distrust of the United States and that it would be impossible for his country to unilaterally renounce its nuclear weapons in these circumstances.
At the World Health Organization’s annual General Assembly, Ri Yong Ho said North Korea had taken “important goodwill measures” last year, such as ending nuclear testing and missile testing, dismantling the nuclear testing site and its commitment not to proliferate nuclear weapons and technology.
"However, we do not see any corresponding response from the United States," he said.
“In the absence of confidence in the United States, we will fear for our national security, and under such circumstances, it is excluded that we will be the first to unilaterally disarm.”
While reiterating North Korea’s well-known accusations of Washington’s opposition to a “step-by-step” approach to denuclearization under which North Korea would be rewarded if it gradually took action, its statement proved important in that it did not reject the idea of a unilateral denuclearization.
Ri referred to a joint statement by Kim Jong Un and Donald Trump, made on June 12 in Singapore at the very first summit between an incumbent US president and a North Korean leader, when Kim pledged to work for “denuclearization of the Korean Peninsula” while Trump promised to ensure North Korea’s security.
North Korea seeks to officially end the Korean War (1950-1953), but the United States has stated that Pyongyang must first renounce its nuclear weapons.
Washington has also denied requests to ease tough international sanctions against North Korea.
The U.S. insists that North Korea first proceed to denuclearization and escalates pressure by imposing sanctions to achieve its goal coercively, even opposing the “end of war declaration.”
“Those who think that these sanctions can make us do it don’t know us.
The problem is that maintaining sanctions increases our mistrust.”
Ri made no comment on the second summit between Kim and Trump highlighted before the United Nations by the US leader earlier this week.
Instead, the minister highlighted three meetings between Kim and South Korean leader Moon Jae-in over the past five months, adding: “If the party involved in the denuclearization issue were South Korea and not the United States, the denuclearization of the Korean Peninsula would not be in such a deadlock.”
Nevertheless, the tone of Ri’s speech was radically different from last year’s, when he told the UN General Assembly that it was inevitable to point North Korean missiles at North American territory after President Trump called Kim a “missile man” on a suicide mission.
Trump, who had threatened the United Nations last year to “totally destroy” North Korea, did not praise this year for the courage with which Kim applied disarmament measures, but added that much still remains to be done and that sanctions would not be lifted until North Korea disarms.
On Wednesday, Trump said no deadline had been set. “It can take two years, three years or five months; it doesn’t matter,” he said.
China and Russia argue that the UN Security Council should reward Pyongyang for the measures adopted.
However, U.S. Secretary of State Mike Pompeo told the UN Security Council last Thursday that: “The implementation of Security Council sanctions must be firmly and systematically maintained until total, final and verified denuclearization.”
The Security Council has unanimously strengthened sanctions against North Korea since 2006 to stifle funding for Pyongyang's nuclear and ballistic missile programmes.
Pompeo met Ri on the sidelines of the UN General Assembly and then announced that he would return to Pyongyang next month to prepare for a second summit.
This year, Pompeo has already visited North Korea three times, but his last trip was somewhat disastrous.
In July, he left Pyongyang claiming that progress had been made but, in the hours that followed, North Korea denounced his “gangster methods.”
At a meeting with Moon this month, North Korea pledged to dismantle a missile site as well as a nuclear complex if the United States took “equivalent measures.”
According to the South Korean president, Kim demands the security guarantees promised by Trump in Singapore, and efforts to normalize relations with Washington.
Harvard: Students take resting classes
This year, Harvard University has put in place a new course that allows all undergraduate students to sleep more and fights the growing macho trend of studying by consuming caffeine all night long.
One professor noticed that most students at the world’s best university don’t know how to take care of them
The course, designed by Charles Czeisler, a professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and a specialist at Brigham and Women's Hospital, is the first of its kind in the United States.
It was after giving a lecture on the effects of sleep deprivation on learning that the idea came to him
At the end, a student came up to me and said, "Why are they only telling me this in the last year?"
She claimed that no one had ever told her about the importance of sleep, which surprised me,” he told The Telegraph.
This course, delivered for the first time this year, explains to students the need to adopt good sleep habits to improve their school and physical performance, as well as their overall well-being.
Paul Barreira, a professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and general director of the university's health services, said the university had decided to introduce the course after finding that students were suffering from a severe lack of sleep during the week.
The course time consists of various interactive exercises.
One of the sections presents the image of a dormitory containing different objects (coffee cups, curtains, sneakers, books...) on which students click to learn about the effects of caffeine and light, as well as the impact of lack of sleep on their physical performance and the importance of integrating a routine before bedtime.
In another section, participants learn how long-term sleep deprivation can increase the risk of heart attack, stroke, depression, and cancer.
A campus map featuring interactive icons then invites participants to reflect on their daily routine.
“We know that this won’t instantly change the behavior of students.
However, in our opinion, they have the right to know this information – in the same way that you have the right to know what the health effects of smoking are,” added Professor Czeisler.
According to him, the culture of pride in “spending a white night” still exists, and he adds that modern technology and the ever-increasing pressure exerted on students make sleep deprivation a growing problem.
Having sufficient and good quality sleep should be students’ “secret weapon” to combat stress, exhaustion and anxiety, he said – even to avoid gaining weight, as lack of sleep puts the brain in innocence mode, making them constantly hungry.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old California student in chemistry and physical biology, helped Professor Czeisler design this course after being one of his students last year during his first year at Harvard.
He claimed that this course had opened his eyes and pushed him to insist that it be proposed to the entire campus.
He hopes that the next step will be to offer all postgraduate students a similar degree program before joining the reputable institution.
Professor Czeisler recommends students to provide an alarm for both bedtime and waketime, and to be aware of the harmful effects of the “blue light” emitted by electronic screens and LED light, which can disrupt their circadian rhythm and lead to sleep disturbances.
