Almanach: The Inventor of the Geiger Meter
And now, a page from our Almanac “Sunday Morning”: On September 30, 1882, 136 years ago today, and THE TOURNAL ACCOUNTANT... was born the future physicist Johannes Wilhelm “Hans” Geiger, in Germany.
Geiger developed a method for detecting and measuring radioactivity; an invention that subsequently gave rise to the device known as the Geiger counter.
A pillar of science since then, the Geiger counter has also become fundamental in pop culture, as seen in the 1950 film "Bells of Coronado", with Roy Rogers and Dale Evans, two unlikely scientists:
One man said, “What is this?”
Rogers: “It’s a Geiger counter, it’s used to look for radioactive minerals, like uranium.
With these headphones, you can really hear the effects of the atoms released into the minerals by radioactivity.”
Evans: “So tell me, it sure jumps here!”
Hans Geiger died in 1945, a few days before his 63rd birthday.
But the invention that bears its name remains.
New cancer vaccine allows the immune system to “detect” cancer cells
A new cancer vaccine allows the immune system to “detect” cancer cells and kill them
In the course of treatment, the vaccine tells the immune system how to recognize cancer cells
This technique involves extracting immune cells from a patient and modifying them in the laboratory.
They can then “detect” a protein that is common to many cancers, and are then re-injected.
An experimental vaccine shows encouraging results in patients with different types of cancer.
A woman who received the vaccine, whose goal is to teach the immune system to recognize cancer cells, saw her ovarian cancer disappear for more than 18 months.
The method consists of extracting immune cells from a patient and modifying them in the laboratory, so that they can detect the HER2 protein common to many cancers, and finally reinjecting them.
Professor Jay Berzofsky, of the U.S. National Cancer Institute based in Bethesda, Maryland, said: “Our results indicate that we have a very promising vaccine.”
According to Professor Berzofsky, the HER2 protein “causes an increase in several types of cancer”, including breast, ovarian, lung and colorectal cancer.
A similar approach, consisting of taking immune cells to “learn” how to target cancer cells, has been proven in the treatment of a type of leukemia.
