The National Trust monitors the secret life of bats
New research conducted in an area of the Scottish Highlands seeks to reveal how bats use the landscape in their quest for food.
It is hoped that the observations will shed new light on the behaviour of these unique flying mammals and will guide future conservation activities.
The National Trust for Scotland researchers’ study will follow common pipistrels and sopranos as well as long-eared brown bats and Daubenton in the garden of Inverewe in Wester Ross.
Special recording devices will be placed in key locations around the property to track bat activities throughout the season.
NHS staff and volunteers will also conduct mobile studies using portable detectors.
A professional sound analysis will determine the frequency of bat cries as well as the activities of the different species.
A map and a report on habitat will be prepared to provide a detailed picture of their behaviour across the territory.
Rob Dewar, nature conservation adviser for the NTS, hopes that the results will reveal the most important areas of habitat for bats and how they are used by each of these species.
This information will determine the benefits of habitat management work such as the creation of meadows and the best way to preserve forests for bats and other related species.
In Scotland and the United Kingdom, bat populations have declined significantly over the last century.
They are threatened by construction and development works that affect the perch and result in the loss of their habitat.
Wind turbines and lighting can also pose a risk, as can fly-kill papers and certain chemical treatments of building materials, as well as pet cat attacks.
Bats aren't really blind.
However, given their nocturnal hunting habits, their ears are more useful than their eyes when it comes to catching prey.
They use a sophisticated echolocation technique to spot insects and obstacles on their flight paths.
Responsible for the protection of more than 270 historic buildings, 38 important gardens and 76,000 hectares of land in the country, the NTS takes bats very seriously.
It has ten trained experts, who regularly conduct surveys, perch inspections and sometimes rescues.
The organization has also established Scotland's first and only bat reserve at the Threave site in Dumfries and Galloway, which is home to eight of Scotland's ten bat species.
David Thompson, the domain manager, says the site is the perfect territory for them.
“Here at Threave, we have a great place for bats,” he says.
“We have old buildings, lots of old trees and all the right habitat.
But there’s still a lot to learn about bats, so the work we do here and elsewhere will help us better understand what bats need to thrive.”
He emphasized the importance of checking for bats before proceeding with the maintenance of the properties, because by unintentionally destroying a single maternity nest, one can thus cause the death of 400 females and young, or even the disappearance of an entire local population.
Bats are protected and it is illegal to kill them, disturb them, or destroy their perch.
Elisabeth Ferrell, the Scottish head of the Bat Conservation Trust, encouraged the public to help.
She said: “We still have a lot to learn about our bats and as far as many of our species are concerned, we don’t know what’s going on in their populations right now.”
