At least 384 people were killed in a powerful earthquake and tsunami that devastated the Indonesian city of Palu on Friday, authorities said, and the balance sheet is expected to tighten.
As communications were paralyzed, emergency services were unable to receive any information from the Donggala Regency, an area north of Palu that is closer to the epicentre of the magnitude 7.5 earthquake.
In Palu, more than 16,000 people were evacuated following the disaster.
Some essential facts about Palu and Donggala, on the island of Sulawesi:
Palu is the capital of the central province of Sulawesi, located at the tip of a narrow bay on the west coast of Sulawesi Island, with an estimated population of 379,800 in 2017.
The city celebrated its 40th anniversary when the earthquake and tsunami occurred.
Donggala is a regency that runs more than 300 km (180 miles) of coastline northwest of Sulawesi Island.
The population of the Regency, an administrative region located below a province, was estimated at 299,200 in 2017.
Fishing and agriculture are the main pillars of the economy of central Sulawesi province, and especially of the coastal region of Donggala.
Nickel mining is also an important activity in the province, but it is mainly located in Morowali, on the opposite coast of Sulawesi.
Palu and Donggala have been hit by tsunamis on several occasions over the past century, according to the Indonesian Disaster Reduction Agency.
In 1938, a tsunami killed more than 200 people and destroyed hundreds of homes in Donggala.
A tsunami also struck west of Donggala in 1996, killing nine people.
Indonesia is located on the seismic fire circle of the Pacific and is regularly shaken by earthquakes.
Here are some of the major earthquakes and tsunamis of recent years:
2004: A major earthquake on the west coast of the Indonesian province of Aceh triggered a tsunami in 14 countries, killing 226,000 people on the Indian Ocean coast, more than half of them in Aceh.
2005: Several violent earthquakes rocked the west coast of Sumatra from late March to early April.
A few hundred people died on the island of Nias, off Sumatra.
2006: A magnitude 6.8 earthquake hit southern Java, Indonesia's most populous island, triggering a tsunami that hit the south coast and killed nearly 700 people.
2009: A 7.6 magnitude earthquake shook the city of Padang, the capital of West Sumatra province.
More than 1,100 people were killed.
2010: A magnitude 7.5 earthquake devastated one of the Mentawai Islands off Sumatra, triggering a more than 10m tsunami that destroyed dozens of villages and killed about 300 people.
2016: A superficial earthquake shook the Regency of Pidie Jaya in Aceh, causing destruction and panic, reminding residents of the devastation caused by the 2004 earthquake and tsunami.
No tsunami was caused this time, but more than 100 people were killed in the collapse of buildings.
2018: Major earthquakes shook the Indonesian tourist island of Lombok, killing more than 500 people, mostly on the north side of the island.
The quake destroyed several thousand buildings and temporarily left thousands of tourists stranded.
